'''Popular Unity''' ({{lang-el|Λαϊκή Ενότητα (ΛΑΕ)}}, ''Laïkí Enótita'', '''LAE''') is a [[left-wing politics|left-wing]]{{r|bbc21aug}}<ref name="eki1"/> [[list of political parties in Greece|political party]] in [[Greece]].

Popular Unity was founded on 21 August 2015 by twenty five parliamentarians formerly affiliated to the [[Syriza|Coalition of the Radical Left]] (Syriza),{{r|bbc21aug}} as a reaction to [[Prime Minister of Greece|Prime Minister]] [[Alexis Tsipras]]' handling of the [[Greek government-debt crisis|Greek bailout agreement of 2015]]. It is led by the former [[Ministry of Productive Reconstruction, Environment and Energy|Minister of Energy]] [[Panagiotis Lafazanis]].{{r|nytimes}} Due to receiving 2.86% (vs. the required 3%) of the popular vote in the September 2015 election it has no seats in the Parliament.{{r|reporter}}

==History==
Popular Unity was founded on 21 August 2015 by 25 parliamentarians formerly affiliated to the [[Syriza|Coalition of the Radical Left]] (Syriza),{{r|bbc21aug}} as a reaction to [[Prime Minister of Greece|Prime Minister]] [[Alexis Tsipras]]' handling of the [[Greek government-debt crisis|Greek bailout agreement of 2015]]. At foundation Popular Unity was the third largest party in the [[Hellenic Parliament|Greek parliament]].{{r|"Kouvelakis"}} It is led by the former [[Ministry of Productive Reconstruction, Environment and Energy|Minister of Energy]] in the [[First Cabinet of Alexis Tsipras|Tsipras cabinet]], [[Panagiotis Lafazanis]].{{r|nytimes}} [[Dimitris Stratoulis]] (former [[Ministry of Labour and Social Solidarity (Greece)#Ministers of Labour and Social Solidarity (since 2015)|Alternate Minister of Social Security]]) and [[Costas Isychos]] (former Alternate Minister of National Defence), who were sacked in July 2015,{{r|ekathimerini}} also joined the new party.

===Election September 2015===
On 2 September 2015, the party programme for the [[Greek legislative election, September 2015|snap election on September 20]] was published.{{r|program}} The party received about 2.9% of the vote, below the 3% threshold to win any seats in parliament. In response to the result the party said, 'we lost the game but not the war'.{{r|reporter}}

==Naming==
The name of the party is inspired by [[Popular Unity (Chile)|Popular Unity]], the [[Chile]]an political alliance led by [[Salvador Allende]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Greece-rebels-form-new-party-ahead-of-snap-polls|title=Greece rebels form new party ahead of snap polls|date=21 August 2015|agency=AFP|accessdate=21 August 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150822184939/http://www.jamaicaobserver.com/latestnews/Greece-rebels-form-new-party-ahead-of-snap-polls|archivedate=22 August 2015|df=}}</ref>

==Policies==
The party favours [[Greek withdrawal from the eurozone|Greek withdrawal]] from the [[eurozone]] and reinstating the [[Greek drachma|drachma]] as Greece's national currency.{{r|bbc21aug}} According to founding member Stathis Kouvelakis, a former member of Syriza's Central Committee, the new party supports [[socialist internationalism]], [[pacifism]], Greece's exit from [[NATO]], and breaking military agreements with [[Israel]].<ref name="Kouvelakis"/>

